TY  - JOUR
T1  - Van de Ven and Johnson's “Engaged Scholarship”: Nice Try, But…
AU  - McKelvey, Bill
Y1  - 2006/10/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2006.22527451
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2006.22527451
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 822
EP  - 829
VL  - 31
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Practitioners find little value in academic research. Some see it as a knowledge flow problem; others see practitioner and academic knowledge as unrelated. Van de Venand Johnson propose a pluralistic collective of researchers and practitioners using ?engaged scholarship? and intellectual arbitrage to create practitioner-meaningful research. It's a nice dream, but not a solution; bias, disciplines, and particularism remain. Neither discipline-centric nor practitioner-driven research offers a solution. Earthquake science offers a better model for business school research.
AB  - Practitioners find little value in academic research. Some see it as a knowledge flow problem; others see practitioner and academic knowledge as unrelated. Van de Venand Johnson propose a pluralistic collective of researchers and practitioners using ?engaged scholarship? and intellectual arbitrage to create practitioner-meaningful research. It's a nice dream, but not a solution; bias, disciplines, and particularism remain. Neither discipline-centric nor practitioner-driven research offers a solution. Earthquake science offers a better model for business school research.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2006.22527451
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2006.22527451
Y2  - 2026/04/24
